{"title_page": "Do-rag", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of men's headscarf to maintain hair positioning}}\n{{Redirect|Durag|the village in Poland|Dur\u0105g|the village in Iran|Durag, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Durag, Iran}}{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}[[File:Gza-01-mika.jpg|thumb|American rapper [[GZA]] wearing a durag]]\n[[File:Master p-02.jpg|thumb|[[Master P]] wearing a durag]]\n\nA '''durag''' or '''do-rag''' or '''du-rag''' also called a '''wave cap''' is a cap typically worn to accelerate the development of [[waves (hairstyle)|waves]], braids or dreadlocks in the hair.<ref>{{citation | author=Tom Dalzell | entry=do-rag | title=The Routledge Dictionary of Modern American Slang and Unconventional English | publisher=Routledge | year=2009 | pages=308 | isbn=978-0-415-37182-7| author-link=Tom Dalzell }}</ref> Durags are also sometimes worn as a fashion statement.\n\n== History ==\nDurags were originally worn by poor African American women laborers and slaves in the 19th century. In the 1930s, during the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and [[Great Depression]], the durag was used to maintain hairstyles. After the [[Black Power Movement]] in the late 1960s, the durag became a [[fashion statement]] among [[African Americans]], worn by rappers, athletes and men of all ages. In the 2000s, wearing durags in public lost popularity in certain areas, but maintained its popularity in others.{{fact|date=September 2019}} However, because of rappers such as [[ASAP Ferg|A$AP Ferg]] and the renewed popularity of [[Waves (hairstyle)|waves]], they regained their status. Now the durag is worn by all genders and races as a fashion statement or to maintain hairstyles.\n\n== Controversy ==\nSome United States high schools attempted to ban the wearing of durags.<ref name=\"Rubio-Dec 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Rubio |first1=Karolena |title=Du-Rag Controversy Resolved |url=https://raidervoice.com/uncategorized/2018/12/13/du-rag-controversy-resolved/ |website=raidervoice.com |accessdate=15 July 2019 |page=1 |language=English |date=13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Miller- July 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Rann |title=A Charter School's Explanation for Banning Durags Is Worse Than the Ban |url=https://progressive.org/public-school-shakedown/charter-schools-explanation-for-banning-durags-worse-than-ban-180720/ |website=progressive.org |accessdate=15 July 2019 |page=1 |language=English |date=20 July 2018}}</ref> When [[John Muir High School]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], [[California]], banned durags as part of a school dress-code policy, the Black Student Union staged a peaceful walk-out in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2019/02/26/california-high-school-students-stage-mass-walkout-over-policy-banning-durags/|title=California High School Students Stage Mass Walkout Over Policy Banning Durags|last=Kenney|first=Tanasia|date=26 February 2019|website=Atlanta Black Star}}</ref> Protesting students contended that school administrators banned the head-wear because of its affiliation with [[gang culture]], although the principal claimed that durags were banned because \"of values we have for how we present ourselves at school\".\n\nIn 2001, the [[National Football League]] banned its players from wearing durags and [[bandana]]s underneath their helmets.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Official NFL Playing Rules, Rule 5: Players, Substitutes, Equipment, General Rules|last=|first=|publisher=National Football League|year=2011|isbn=|location=|pages=29}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[Merriam-Webster]] placed the earliest usage of \"do-rag\" in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/do-rag|title=do-rag|website=Merriam-Webster|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> However, ''[[The New York Times]]'' claims that the true spelling of the word is \"durag,\" and its popularity began in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/14/style/durag-solange-met-gala.html|title=The Durag, Explained|last=Garcia|first=Sandra E.|date=14 May 2018|website=The New York Times|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> An alternative etymology claimed that \"do-rag\" is \"dew-rag\", and \"dew\" is a euphemism for sweat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://listserv.linguistlist.org/pipermail/ads-l/2005-March/046931.html|title=Do-Rag (1966)|last=Preston|first=Dennis R.|date=23 March 2005|website=Lingualist|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnd in the 1950s in Brooklyn, 'do-rag' was a commonplace term\n\nOn June 4, 1966, The Akron Beacon Journal printed \"do rag&nbsp;... a cloth band worn around the forehead as a sweatband or to keep hair in place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152630510/|title=Akron Beacon Journal, June 4, 1966}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1966, \"do rag&nbsp;... processed hair done up in black rags\" appeared in Newsweek.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=%22+the+do+rag+%22&biw=1366&bih=614&source=lnt&tbs=cdr%3A1%2Ccd_min%3A1%2F1%2F1955%2Ccd_max%3A12%2F31%2F1966&tbm=bks |title=Newsweek, Vol. 68, Oct-Dec 1966, Page 31}}</ref>\n\n== Popular Culture ==\nAmerican singer and bassist [[Thundercat (musician)|Thundercat's]] album [[Thundercat (musician)|''It Is What It Is'']] features the song entitled \"Dragonball Durag\"''.'' The lyrics references the headwear as the title piece to impress women. The durag referenced has a pattern taken from popular Japanese television cartoon [[Dragon Ball]]. \n\nRapper [[Royce da 5'9\"]] has a song on the 2020 album ''[[The Allegory]]'' entitled \"Rhinestone Doo Rag\". \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kerchief]]\n* [[List of headgear]]\n* [[Cap]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|People wearing do-rags}}\n\n[[Category:Headgear]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of men's headscarf to maintain hair positioning}}\n{{Redirect|Durag|the village in Poland|Dur\u0105g|the village in Iran|Durag, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Durag, Iran}}{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}[[File:Gza-01-mika.jpg|thumb|American rapper [[GZA]] wearing a durag]]\n[[File:Master p-02.jpg|thumb|[[Master P]] wearing a durag]]\n\nA '''durag''' or '''do-rag''' or '''du-rag''' also called a '''wave cap''' is a cap typically worn to accelerate the development of [[waves (hairstyle)|waves]], braids or dreadlocks in the hair.<ref>{{citation | author=Tom Dalzell | entry=do-rag | title=The Routledge Dictionary of Modern American Slang and Unconventional English | publisher=Routledge | year=2009 | pages=308 | isbn=978-0-415-37182-7| author-link=Tom Dalzell }}</ref> Durags are also sometimes worn as a fashion statement.\n\n== History ==\nDurags were originally worn by poor African American women laborers and slaves in the 19th century. In the 1930s, during the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and [[Great Depression]], the durag was used to maintain hairstyles. After the [[Black Power Movement]] in the late 1960s, the durag became a [[fashion statement]] among [[African Americans]], worn by rappers, athletes and men of all ages. In the 2000s, wearing durags in public lost popularity in certain areas, but maintained its popularity in others.{{fact|date=September 2019}} However, because of rappers such as [[ASAP Ferg|A$AP Ferg]] and the renewed popularity of [[Waves (hairstyle)|waves]], they regained their status. Now the Durag is worn by all genders and races as a fashion statement or to maintain hairstyles.\n\n== Controversy ==\nSome United States high schools attempted to ban the wearing of durags.<ref name=\"Rubio-Dec 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Rubio |first1=Karolena |title=Du-Rag Controversy Resolved |url=https://raidervoice.com/uncategorized/2018/12/13/du-rag-controversy-resolved/ |website=raidervoice.com |accessdate=15 July 2019 |page=1 |language=English |date=13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Miller- July 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Rann |title=A Charter School's Explanation for Banning Durags Is Worse Than the Ban |url=https://progressive.