v.linguistlist.org/pipermail/ads-l/2005-March/046931.html|title=Do-Rag (1966)|last=Preston|first=Dennis R.|date=23 March 2005|website=Lingualist|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnd in the 1950s in Brooklyn, 'do-rag' was a commonplace term\n\nOn June 4, 1966, The Akron Beacon Journal printed \"do rag&nbsp;... a cloth band worn around the forehead as a sweatband or to keep hair in place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152630510/|title=Akron Beacon Journal, June 4, 1966}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1966, \"do rag&nbsp;... processed hair done up in black rags\" appeared in Newsweek.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=%22+the+do+rag+%22&biw=1366&bih=614&source=lnt&tbs=cdr%3A1%2Ccd_min%3A1%2F1%2F1955%2Ccd_max%3A12%2F31%2F1966&tbm=bks |title=Newsweek, Vol. 68, Oct-Dec 1966, Page 31}}</ref>\n\n== Popular Culture ==\nAmerican singer and bassist [[Thundercat (musician)|Thundercat's]] album [[Thundercat (musician)|''It Is What It Is'']] features the song entitled \"Dragonball Durag\"''.'' The lyrics references the headwear as the title piece to impress women. The durag referenced has a pattern taken from popular Japanese television cartoon [[Dragon Ball]]. \n\nRapper [[Royce da 5'9\"]] has a song on the 2020 album ''[[The Allegory]]'' entitled \"Rhinestone Doo Rag\". \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kerchief]]\n* [[List of headgear]]\n* [[Cap]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|People wearing do-rags}}\n\n[[Category:Headgear]]\n", "name_user": "Thtatithticth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Capitalization: \"Durag\" \u2192 \"durag\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Do-rag"}
